column168: Description Of Events

PRAXIS WAS HAVING DRIVER "TOP OFF" A STORAGE TANK WHILE THE OPERATOR WAS WATCHING THE SITE GLASS WAS DEFECTIVE AS THE DRIVER, WHO WAS STANDING NEAR HIS CONTROL VALVE, THEN SAW PRODUCT RUNNING FROM AN OVERFLOW VALVE. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF HIS VALVE, THEN SHUT OFF HIS PUMP. THE STORAGE TANK WAS IN A BUILDING WHERE THE DRIVER COULDN'T SEE IT AND THE OPERATOR COULDN'T SEE THAT THE PIPE WAS OVERFLOWING. OPERATOR THAT STORAGE TANK HAD OVERFLOWED. SITE GLASS WAS SHOWING TANK JUST OVER HALF FULL. PLANT PERSONNEL PLACED SAND AROUND THE SPILL TO CONTAIN IT THEN THEY TOOK CARE OF CLEANUP. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS WAS SPILLED, WHICH WOULD BE NEAR 800 POUNDS.

GATX 11055 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS NY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED ND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, GATX MOBILE REPAIR SERVICES, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE PACKING AROUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING ROD DETERIORATED ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE FROM AROUND THE ROD. THE REPLACED AND THEE PACKING GLAD NUTS PROPERLY SECURED RELEASE.

AN ASSOCIATE WAS IN THE LOADING/ UNLOADING PROCESS, WHEN THE DRUM TRUCKS THAT HE WAS USING PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSING APPROX/ GALLON TO BE RELEASED. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP FOR PROPER DISPOSITION THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE DRUM, PACKED OVER PACKED AND RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER FOR HANDLING.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED WHILE IN THE FED EX WAREHOUSE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS A RE-USED COFFEE CAN WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PAINT.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS POORLY CONSTRUCTED AND APPEARED TO BE CARDBOARD THAT THE SHIPPER HAD TAPED TO CREATE THE BOX.  THE PAINT WOULD NOT WASH UP EASILY.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT IT IS NOT LATEX.  PROPER SPILL CLEAN UP PROCEDURES OCCURRED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE PACKAGE WAS NO SENT WITH ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELING, OR A SHIPPERS DECLARATION, AND IS SUSPECTED TO BE OIL BASE PAINT, NAMELY PAINT UN1263.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO PROVIDE A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET BUT THEY DID NOT HAVE ONE AVAILABLE.  AS THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PAINT IS UNKNOWN DUE TO THE INNER CONTAINER NOT BEING THE ORIGINAL ONE TO THE PAINT, WE COULD NOT CONTACT THEM FOR AN MSDS.  THE SHIPMENT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  F.A.A. AGENT CATE ZAMPARELLI WAS NOTIFIED ON 08021999 08:40CT.  FED EX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HER INVESTIGATION.

THE BAY OF MATERIAL WAS TORN AS THE WAREHOUSEMAN ATTEMPTED TO LOAD TH PAL LETS SIDE BY SIDE. THE BAG WAS TORN BY THE OTHER PALLET. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PUT INTO A RECOVERY PAIL AND THE TORN BAG WAS RECOOPED.

AT 20.00 HOURS I WAS INFORMED OF A HAZMAT LEAK BY LEAD MAN STAN MCMURRY. I WENT TO THE TRAILER, SEEN THE LEAK, NOTICED A POISON STICKER ON THE DRUM FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, PULLED THE DOOR DOWN GOT THE BILL OF LADEN, DID A QUITE INFORMATION INTERVIEW WITH THE DOCKMAN RESPONSIBLE (ZELL HAND) RETURNED TO THE OFFICE. I THEN QUICKLY CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK. I THEN TOLD STAN TO SCOURE THE AREA AND KEEP OUT THE VAPORS, I THEN CALLED EDDIE YANCE, OUR HAZMAT SPECIALIST IN GENERAL OFFICE AT 2005 HOURS. AFTER EX PLANING ALL THE DETAILS TO MR. YANCE I FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTIONS. THEY WERE 1) KEEP AREA SECURED . 2) CALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE # ON THE BILL. 3) CONTAIN LEAK USING OUR SANDPILE KEEPING A SAFE DISTANCE FROM SPILL. 4) KEEP HIM INFORMED OF ANY CHANGES IN THE SITUATION. I FINELY GOT MR. DAVID CRAG FROM DETREX AT 20:50 HOURS. HE WAS MY CONTACT FROM THE EMERGENCY REPONCE # ON THE BILL OF LADEN.HE WAS ON THE ROAD. HE HAD TO RETURN TO HIS OFFICE BEFORE HE COULD SEND ME THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS I REQUESTED. I RECEIVED THE MSDS AT 21:30 HOURS. THE CHEMICAL CLEAN UP CREW FROM HAPCO, (EDDIE YANCE CONTACTED THEM ARRIVED HERE AT THE TERMINAL AT 20:35 HOURS. THERE TRUCK WITH CLEAN UP BEGIN CLEANING UP HTE SPILL. THE HAPCO CREW FINISHED UP. PUT THE HAZ MAT WASTE MATERIAL IN CONTAINERS AND PUT IT IN OUR OST&D BTY. ADVISED ME TO LET THE TRAILER AIR-OUT FOR A COUPLE OF DAYS OUT ON THE YD. THEY WERE ALSO  ABLE TO ADVISE ME THROUGH THERE INVESTIGATION THAT THE DRUM THAT WAS BASTED WAS DONE BY A SHARP OBJECT HITTING IT ABOUT A FOOT UP FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. ZELL HAND, THE DRUM LIFTER. THERE ARE SHARP CORNERS ON THE FRAMING OF THIS PC OF EQUIPMENT. ZELL TOLD  ME THAT HE CAUSED BY THE PERSON LOADING THE DRUMS BECAUSE THEY WERE LOADED SO TIGHT AGAINST EACH OTHER. THEN WHEN HE FREAD ONE IT BEGIN LEAKING. HE SAID HE TOLD ME THIS. HE WENT HOME BEFORE THE CREW BEGAN THERE CLEAN UP. I WILL INTERVIEW HIM AGAIN TOMORROW. TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE.

AT APPROX. 19:40 I WAS INFORMED BY MY LEADMAN THAT I HAD A HAZAMT SPILL, IN DOOR EIGHT. I WENT DOWN RECEIVED THE BILL, CHECKED THE HAZMAT INFORMATION AND BECAUSE IT WAS A CLASS 9 MOSQUITO REPELLENT I OPENED THE DOOR TO INVESTIGATE THE SPILL. I SEEN LIQUID POURING OUT OF A DRUM. I WALKED INTO THE TRAILER TURNED THE DRUM OVER TO STOP THE LEAK CAME OUT OF THE TRAILER PULLED THE DOOR DOWN AND IMMEDITLY CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE HAND BOOK. I THEN CALLED OUR HAZ MAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM DOTHAN AND TALKED WITH EDDIE YANCE. I GAVE HIM ALL THE INFORMATION AND THEN FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTIONS. THIS WAS AT 20:00 HOURS. HIS INSTRUCTIONS WERE AS FOLLOWS. 1) CONTAINE THE SPILL ON THE YD THAT WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER WIT SAND. AND ABSORBENT. 2) CALL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE # ON THE BILL AND GET A SAFETY DATA SHEET. FAX TO ME. 3) COORDINATE WITH HAPECO , THE HAZMAT CLEAN UP CREW AT THE CLEAN UP PROCESS. I FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS. HAPECO CONTACTED ME AT APPROX. 20:45 HOURS. THEY WERE HERE CLEANING AT 21:00 HOURS AND WERE FINISHED BY 23:00 HOURS. THEY SUGGESTED THAT THE TRAILER AIR UOT FOR A DAY AND THEN BE STEAMED CLEANED. HAPECO INFORMATION INCLUDING PICTURES, WILL BE SENT DIRECTLY TO EDDIE YANCE. AFTER ALL THE INITIAL CONTACT WERE MADE I INTERVIEWEDTHOMAS LESSING, THE EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE HAZMAT SPILL. HE SAID THAT HE DIDN'T THINK HE WAS THAT CLOSE TO THE DRUM. ONE OF HIS BLADES WAS STICKING OUT OF THE SKID HE WAS LOADING BEHIND THESE DRUMS AND HE PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH THE END OF THE BLADE. THOMAS HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED SEVERAL TIME TO USE DUNNAGE WHEN LOADING AROUND DRAMS. HE FAILED TO DO SO THIS TIME. I EX PLANED THE IMPORTANCE OF USING EXTREME CAUTION WHEN DEALING WITH HAZMAT AND HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO USE DUNNAGE EACH AND EVERY TIME HE LOAD AROUND THEM. I EXPLAINED ALL THE COAST THAT WAS GOING TO BE INVOLVED BECAUSE OF HIS EXPENSIVE MISTAKE. AFTER I WAS SURE HE UNDERSTOOD ALL OF THIS I INSTRUCTED HIM OF THE CORRECTIVE ACTION HE WOULD RECEIVE. 1ST) HE WILL PUNCH OFF THE CLOCK FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE DAY. 2ND) HE WOULD RECEIVE THE FOLLOWING DAY OFF WITHOUT PAY. 3RD) IF HE IN THE FUTURE, IS INVOLVED IN ANOTHER LOADING OR UNLOADING MISTAKE LIKE THIS HE WILL BE SUBJECTED TOO MORE TIME OFF WITHOUT PAY UP TO TERMINATION OF EMPLOYMENT.

SR-- 238 WAS CLOSED FROM ABOUT 1424 TO 1500.  FERTIZONA PERSONNEL ARRIVED ABOUT 1445 AN CLOSED THE VALVE, STOPPING THE LEAK.  ONE PERSON WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WITH SECOND DEGREE BURNS ON HIS ARM.  NH-3 HANDLER SHOULD ALWAYS BE INSTRUCTED TO CLOSE VALVES BEFORE ADJUSTING REGULATORS.

THE TWO DRUMS HAD ALREADY BEEN LOADED ON THE OUTBOUND TRAILER. A FORKLIFT OPERATOR LOADED A SKID OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF ANOTHER SKID O FREIGHT THAT WAS BEHIND THE DRUMS. APPARENTLY DURING THE LOADING PROCESS A PART OF THE FORKLIFT MAST STRUCK THE DRUM CAUSING A PUNCTURE WITH APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF LIQUID LEAKING OUT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM SHORTLY AFTER THE INCIDENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNIT, AND RESCUE UNIT RESPONDED AFTER BEING NOTIFIED. THE HAZ MAT UNIT NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL MATERIAL WITH BAKING SODA AND THE RESCUE UNIT CHECKED EIGHT PEOPLE FOR VITAL SIGNS AFTER THEY INHALED SOME OF THE FUMES. EVERYONE CHECKED OUT OK. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WHO CAUSED THE DAMAGED WAS ISSUED CORRECTIVE ACTION WHICH INCLUDED REMEDIAL FORKLIFT TRAINING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THIS REPORT IS MADE DUE TO A VEHICULAR ACCIDENT THAT RESULTED IN THE HIGHWAY BEING SHUT DOWN FOR ONE HOUR OR MORE AND THE DRIVER FATALLY INJURED IN THE ACCIDENT. THERE WAS NO LOSS OF PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK. THERE WAS A RUPTURE OF THE SADDLE TANK AND A FIRE ENSUED WHICH CONSUMED THE TRACTOR. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. OUR UNIT WAS TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON THE WESTERN KENTUCKY PARKWAY WHEN IT REAR ENDED A UNIT ON THE EMERGENCY LANE AFTER IMPACT OUR UNIT VEERED OFF TO THE LEFT WHERE IT WENT INTO THE MEDIAN AND OVERTURNED. THE TRACTOR CAUGHT FIRE AND BURNED COMPLETELY WITH THE DRIVER INSIDE. DUE TO THE FIRE AND CONTENTS OF THE TANK BEING COMBUSTIBLE THE HIGHWAY WAS SHUT DOWN UNTILL THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AND THE INSPECTED TO ASSURE THAT THERE WAS NO LOSS OF CARGO. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO A SERVICEABLE CARGO TANK WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1945 HOURS, SUNDAY, AUGUST 1, 1999, AT PAVONIA YARD IN CAMDEN, NJ, A CAR DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE NOTED ODORS EMANATING FROM TANK CAR TILX 301479 CONTAINING AMMONIA,ANHYDROUS. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 2215 HOURS, ON AUGUST 1, 1999, CONRAIL'S MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND REACT ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN; CLOSURE PLUG FOR SAID VALVE NOT TOOL TIGHT AND ALL TWENTY MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE SECUREMENT NUTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REACT WHO CLOSED THE "A"  END VALVE , SECURED PLUG AND ALL TWENTY PRESSURE PLATE SECUREMENT NUTS. AT APPROXIMATELY 0355 HOURS, AUGUST 2,1999, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1615 HOURS, MONDAY AUGUST2, 1999, AT CONRAILS OAK ISLAND YARD IN NEWARK, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 201397 CONTAINING PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1645 HOURS, CONRAILS MANAGER CAR INSPECTION AND REPAIR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WERE TWO MANYWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS, CONRAILS MANAGER CAR INSPECTION AND REPAIR TIGHTENED THE TWO MANWAY COIVER SECUREMENT BOLTS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1905 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS OKAY FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: OUR LOADED UNIT WAS NORTH BOUND ON INTERSTATE 45 WHEN THE DRIVER ALLEGES HE FELL ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL.  THE UNIT DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD HIT A METAL GUARD RAIL AND ROLLED OVER INTO THE GRASS.  THE TRACTOR CAUGHT FIRE, AND THE FRONT CLEAN OUT CAP STARTED DRIPPING WHEN THE TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE.

UNIT WAS WEST BOUND ON ROUTE 412 EAST OF ENID, OK AND WAS STOPPING AT RAILROAD TRACKS WHEN DRIVER SA AMMONIA VAPOR LEAKING OUT OF THE END OF THE UNLOADING HOSE IN HOSE RACK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND CHECKED VALVES.  DRIVER CALLED THE COMPANY AND THE FIRE DEPT WAS DISPATCHED.  UPON ARRIVAL THE FIRE DEPT TRIED THE VALVES AGAIN AND TURNED THE LIQUID VALVE ON UNLOADING LINE LESS THAN A QUARTER OF A TURN AND STOPPED LEAK.  THE FIRE DEPT RINSED OFF SIDE OF TRAILER AND SHOULDER OF ROAD AND LEFT.  THE TRUCK RETURNED TO FARMLAND PLANT, SECURED THE LOADING LINE WITH A STEEL CAP AND DELIVERED LOAD.

DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS A LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE PRODUCT PUMP THAT IS MOUNTED ON THE TRUCK TRACTOR. UPON NOTICE OF THE LEAK A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE PUMP TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF RESIN LEAKED DURING THE OFF LOADING PROCESS. THE POSITIVE DISPLACEMENT PRODUCT PUMP BEGAN LEAKING DUE TO WORN PACKING. THE PUMP PACKING HAS BEEN REPLACED AND MUST HAVE REGULAR MAINTENANCE TO ASSURE FUTURE LEAKAGE

OUR VEHICLE WAS AT THE CONSIGNEE UNLOADING SITE AND IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS. WHEN A SLKHT LEAK WAS DETECTED. OUR DRIVER WAS ALERTED OF THE LEAK AND SHUT DOWN THE PROCESS IN DOING SO PRODUCT THAT WAS IN THE CUSTOMERS PRODUCT LINE (WHICH EXTENDS VERTICALLY ABOUT 20 INCH THEN HORIZONTALLY FOR AN UNKNOWN DISTANCE) BEGAN DISCHARGING AT A RAPID RATE. THE ACID WAS SPRAYING ON THE CUT OFF VALVE WHICH WAS LOCATED LESS THAN ONE FOOT FROM THE LEAK. FOR PERSONAL SAFETY REASONS THE VALVE WAS NOT TURNED OFF UNTILL THE SPRAY WAS REDUCED. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A DAMAGED GASKET THAT IS PLACED BETWEEN THE 4 BOLT FLANGE CONNECTION ON THE PRODUCT HOSE AND THE CUSTOMERS 4 BOLT FLANGE CONNECTION. THE CONSIGNEE HANDLED REMEDIATION.

OUR DRIVER PICKED UP TRAILER THAT WAS LOADED BY SAFETY KLEEN IN PECATONICA, IL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT OUR DROP YARD IN LA PORTE, TX., HE OPENED TRAILER TO CHECK LOAD AND NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR.  3E WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVER PACKED AND TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATE.

DISCOVERED AN ODOR FROM INSIDE TRAILER 315-5034, DURING UNLOADING AND UPON IDENTIFYING  MATERIAL OUR H/M VENDOR WAS CALLED IN ADDITION OF CONTACTING SHIPPER.  H/M VENDOR EXAMINED ONE METAL PAIL AND IT WAS LEAKING FROM SIDE SEAM - POSSIBLE METAL FATIGUE?
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DSR WAS UNLOADING A 55-GALLON DRUM WITH A HAND DOLLIE.  WHEN THE WHEEL OF THE DOLLIE WENT OVER DOCK PLATE CAUSING THE DRUM TO JUMP OFF THE CART PUNCTURING THE SIDE OF THE DRUM RIGHT ABOVE THE BOTTOM RIM.  THE MATERIAL REACTED WITH THE MOISTURE IN THE AIR, CREATING STRONG ACID FUMES TO WHERE THE DOCK HAD TO BE CHEM OFF UNTIL THE SPILL WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED-UP.

XCD DSR PUNCTURE 1-2.5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER ON A BROKER SKID WHILE  LOADING  THE PRODUCT INTO HIS TRAILER.  PRODUCT WAS OK UNTIL IT WAS LOADED.  SKID ON TRAILER WAS BROKEN AND A LOOSE BOARD WAS NOT SEEN ON SIDE ON SIDE OF SKID.  UPON LOADING, THIS BOARD  PUNCTURED A HOLE INTO 1- 2.5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER.

LOADER PLACED SKID WITH TWO DRUMS ON BACK OF TRAILER.  THE SKID WAS AT A SLIGHT ANGLE , NOT ALLOWING OTHER FREIGHT TO BE LOADED BESIDE THIS SKID.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO "SPIN" THIS PALLET WITH THE FORKLIFT, ONE FORK "POPPED"  UP AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.
DURING UNLOADING THE CARTON WAS FOUND LEAKING.  OTHER FREIGHT HAD SHIFTED AGAINST THE CARTON PUNCTURING 2-12 OZ. CANS.  THE CARTON WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM.

column168: AT 2100 ON WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 25, 1999 WHILE SWITCHING AT BROWNVILLE JCT THE CONDUCTOR OF NO. 220 (BROWNVILLE SWITCHER) OBSERVED A SMALL FIRE ON THE GROUND UNDER UTLX 200673 HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  APPARENTLY DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS THE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED FROM THE DOME AREA OF THE TANK CAR AND DRIPPED ONTO THE GROUND IGNITING COMBUSTIBLES AT THE POINT OF IMPACT.  THE BROWNVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AT 2101 BY B&A PERSONNEL AT NORTHERN MAINE JCT AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 2117,  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HANDLED THE SITUATION USING COPIOUS AMOUNTS WATER.  INSPECTION OF THE DOME AREA BY THE BROWNVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT REVEALED SIX MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE. THEY TIGHTENED FOUR BOLTS IN A ROW TWO FULL TURNS AND TOW BOLTS 1/2 TURN EACH.  LOGISTICS MANAGEMENT SYSTEM PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE BOLTS AND DOME AREA ON THURSDAY, AUGUST 26, 1999 AND THEN RELEASED THE CAR FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT TO THE FINAL DESTINATION IN HAMPDEN, MAINE.  KEN REID, SAFETY MANAGER FOR THE SHIPPER, (713-307-3417) WAS ADVISED ABOUT THE LOOSE DOME BOLTS AND SAID HE WOULD CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  THE SHIPPER ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS DURING THIS EVENT AT ABOUT ONE GALLON.

LINER NOT INTENDED TO HOLD MOISTURE, FAILED TO HOLD WETNESS OF PRODUCT.  ROLL-OFF CONTAINER NOT DESIGNED TO HOLD WETNESS OF PRODUCT EITHER. column168: DRIVER HAD LOADED NITRIC ACIT AT DYNO NOBEL IN LOUISIANNA, MO AND WAS ON HIS WAY TO CARTHAGE, MO TO DEL. PRIOR TO TAKING A BREAK IN A TRUCK STOP, DRIVER CHECKED HIS VEHICLE AND FOUND MATERIAL LEAKING THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR. WHEN DISCOVERED, VIRTUALLY THE ENTIRE CONTENT OF ONE DRUM HAD LEAKED OUT. THAT WHICH WAS STILL LEAKING WAS DRYING RAPIDLY. THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS A PAIL WHICH HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A PORTABLE TANK THAT WAS NEXT TO IT IN THE TRAILER. DRIVER ACQUIRED, PUT DOWN ABSORBENT MATERIAL WHICH SOAKED UP THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID. VEHICLE WAS THEN ABLE  TO CONTINUE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENTS.

USING ABSORBENT AND MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT, THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN AND CONTROL THE SPILL SUFFICIENTLY TO ALLOW HIM TO PROCEED TO A NEARBY FACILITY OF THE CARRIER.  LEAKING DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE LOAD AND OVERPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

PAIL WAS DAMAGED DURING HANDLING THE CARRIER'S ORIGIN FACILITY. DAMAGE WENT UNNOTICED UNTIL UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S DESTINATION FACILITY.  PAIL WAS OVERPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. TRAILER WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND SENT TO A WASHOUT CONTRACTOR.

column168: AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP THE DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAKAGE FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM.  HE WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE LEAKAGE WITH MATERIALS FROM THE SPILL KIT.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO THE CARRIER'S NEARBY FACILITY.  THE DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF THERE, OVERPACKED AND SUBSEQUENTLY DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.
AT TIME OF DELIVERY, THE DRIVER OBSERVED A RING OF WETNESS AROUND THE BASE OF ONE DRUM.  IT APPEARS TO BE FROM A CRACK AT BOTTOM CHIME AREA.  CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED DELIVERY WITH A EXCEPTION NOTATION.

DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO A CONSIGNEE WHO HAS NO DOCK AND NO LIFT TRUCK.  DURING REMOVAL FROM THE VEHICLE, THE DRUM WAS DROPPED AND STRUCK AND STRUCK A PIECE OF CINDER BLOCK, CAUSING A PINHOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  DRIVER STATES THAT HE CAME INTO CONTACT WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL EXITED THROUGH THE PINHOLE.  HE FELT A BURNING SENSATION AT THE POINT OF CONTACT.  HE IMMEDIATELY RINSED THE AFFECTED AREA WHICH RELIEVED THE SYMPTOMS.  HE DECLINED MEDICAL ATTENTION AND THE SYMPTOMS HAVE NOT RECURRED.  CARRIER IS IN POSSESSION OF MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT.  CONSIGNEE HAD BEEN DESIGNATED AS "LIFT GATE SERVICE ONLY."

ON ARRIVAL AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, THE TANK SHOWED LEAKAGE FROM A WELD CRACK IN ITS TOP SURFACE.  ON ADVICE OF THE SHIPPER, A CONTRACTOR WAS RETAINED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO DRUMS.  THE DRUMS OF PRODUCT AND THE EMPTIED TANK WERE THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

WHEN AIRCRAFT ARRIVED INTO ANC AND THE REAR BELLY WAS OPENED THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR OF PROPANE.  THE PILOT WAS CALLED DOWN FROM THE COCKPIT AND IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE PASSENGERS WOULD BE OFF LOADED AND THE AIRCRAFT COMPLETELY SHUTDOWN UNTIL THE SOURCE OF THE PROPANE WAS FOUND AND THE CARGO PIT WAS VENTED CLEAN.  AFTER OFF LOADING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE REAR PIT, THE SOURCE OF THE PROPANE WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PROPANE BOTTLE WAS INSIDE A CARDBOARD BOX.  THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS LABEL OR MARKINGS OF ANY KIND ON THE BOX. IT WAS PART OF A FIVE PIECE CARGO SHIPMENT.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED.

MISSION DRIVER WAS LOADING AT THE DIAMOND SHAMROCK LOCATION IN THREE RIVERS. THE API VALUE ON COMPARTMENT #4 FLANGE GASKET BLEW CAUSING A 10 GALLON SPILL OF LIGHT OIL. PASCHALL DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE AND THEY BEGAN TO UNLOAD HIM. ABOUT 3/4 OF THE WAY INTO UNLOADING THE CONSIGNEE DISCOVERED A LEAK ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE PASCHALL DRIVER CALLED PTL AND WE CALLED EMI WHO CONTRACTED A SUBCONTRACTOR IN THE HOUSTON AREA TO COME OUT AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT (1) 55 GALLON DRUM WAS INVOLVED. IT HAD LEAKED AROUND THE SEAM ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR.IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ABOUT 2 GALLONS WAS LOST AND IT COVERED A 2 BY 4 FT AREA CLEANED UP THE SPILL AREA. EMI WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DISPOSAL OF THE PRODUCT. DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO NEXT DISPATCH.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0820 A TANKER WAS UNLOADING DIESEL FUEL AND WHILE THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS GOING ON, TOM HUNT NOTICED DIESEL FUEL SPRAYING OUT OF THE PIPE TRENCH AND SHUT DOWN THE SYSTEM. AFTER LIFTING THE FLOOR GRATE WE FOUND THAT ONE OF THE FIBER GLASS PIPES HAD SEPARATED AT A GLUED JOINT AT AN ELBOW. WE CALLED SAFETY KLEEN TO PUMP OUT THE TRENCH. SAFETY KLEEN REMOVED ABOUT 150 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND THE SHOP PERSONNEL PUMPED OUT APPROXIMATELY 120 GALLONS. AT THIS TIME A VENDOR IS REPAIRING THE PIPING AND WHEN THIS IS COMPLETED ANOTHER VENDOR WILL BE CALLED TO CLEAN OUT THE TRENCH. ALL OF THE PRODUCT IS CONTAINED IN THE CONCRETE TRENCH.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING A PALLET OF WASTE FROM ONE AREA OF STORAGE TO ANOTHER IN PREPARATION FOR LOADING ONTO A TRUCK. THE EMPLOYEE DROVE THE FORKLIFT OF PALLETIZED WASTE OVER THE CONTAINMENT BURN CAUSING ONE 5 GALLON DRUM TO FALL TO THE GROUND. WHEN THE DRUM STRUCK THE PAVEMENT IT LEAKED APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF WASTE ONTO THE FLOOR. THE DRIVER ABSORBED AND RECOVERED THE SPILL MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER DRUM AND TIGHTENED THE LID ON THE DROPPED DRUM. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY  FIVE POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY- KLEEN FACILITY AT 960 TURNPIKE ST, CANT MA FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE DIVER WAS BRIEFED ON SAFE FORKLIFT DRIVING PROCEDURES AND COUNSELED TO USE GREATER CARE WHILE LOADING WASTE DRUMS.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSFERRING A GAYLORD BOX FROM A CRUSHED PALET TO A NEW PALLET USING A FORKLIFT. THE BOX FELL OFF THE FORKS, RUPTURING A SEAM, AND SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 40 POUNDS OF CHROMIIUM METAL SHAVINGS ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR. ALL OF THE WASTE MATERIAL FROM THE DAMAGED BOX AS WELL AS THE SPILL SHAVINGS WERE REPACKAGED INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS. THIS SPILL GENERATED 80 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 500 BATTLEGROUND ROAD,LA PORTE, TX FOR CONSOLIDATION AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED IN A REVIEW OF APPROVED OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR SECURING LOADS AND TRANSPORTING MATERIALS WITH A FORKLIFT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON AUGUST 4, 1999 HARRY OWEN TRUCKING WAS TRANSPORTING A SHIPMENT OF SILICONE LIQUIDS FROM A DOW-CORNING FACILITY TO A PROCTOR GAMBLE FACILITY IN HUNT VALLEY, MD. THE DRIVER, DAVE EMERT, WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON I-68 WHEN HE WAS BLINDED BY THE SUN. WHEN DAVE GOT HIS SIGHT BACK HE REALIZED HE WAS TOO FAR OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND COULD NOT ADJUST. BOTH THE TRUCK AND THE TRAILER TURNED OVER. THE TRAILER WAS FILLED WITH NINE TOTES OF THE SILICONE LIQUIDS. LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE BROUGHT TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY. AT 8:00 AM LIBERTY INSURANCE WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE INCIDENT. AT 9:30 AM AN ADJUSTER FROM CRAWFORD AND CO. ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. AROUND 10:30 AM A CLEAN UP COMPANY WERE CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER WAS IMMEDIATELY SUSPENDED FOR 10 DAYS AND RE-TRAINED ON SPEED AND SPACE MANAGEMENT. SAFETY HAS ALSO TAKEN THE TIME TO ADDRESS LOADING PROCEDURES AND INVESTED IN ADDITIONAL TRAINING CLASSES ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING, LOAD MANAGEMENT AND SECUREMENT. DOW CORNING IS AWARE ON THE SEAL/GASKET PROBLEM AND THEY WILL TAKE THE NECESSARY STEPS TO CORRECT THE SEAL/GASKET PROBLEM ON THEIR END. HARRY OWEN TRUCKING IS WORKING WITH EACH OF ITS DRIVER TO ENSURE THAT ANY LOAD A DRIVER ACCEPTS MUST BE PROPERLY LOADED AND BRACED. THE CAUSE OF SPILL WAS TWO FOLD: 1) HARRY OWEN TRUCKING DRIVER USING POOR JUDGEMENT AND DRIVING SKILLS. THE DRIVER AND HARRY OWEN TRUCKING TAKE FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE INITIAL ACCIDENT. THE TIPPING OF THE TRUCK WAS DUE TO DIFFERENT FACTORS; SUNLIGHT, POOR REACTION BY HARRY OWEN TRUCKING DRIVER AND NO ROOM ON SHOULDER FOR DRIVER TO CORRECT HIS MISTAKE. 2) IMPROPER SEALING OF THE IBC TOTES. BASED UPON THE SITE INVESTIGATION THE VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION THE LEAKAGE FORM THE CONTAINERS WAS DUE TO IMPROPER INSTALLATION OF THE SEAL/ GASKETS ON THE CONTAINERS. IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT EIGHT OF THE NINE BUNGS ON THE CONTAINERS WERE TIGHTENED. ONCE THE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED THE CONTAINERS WERE SENT BACK TO DOW CORNING CORPORATION IN CARROLLTON, KY. THE HARRY OWEN TRUCKING DRIVER, DAVE EMERT, WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND EVALUATED. A DRUG AND ALCOHOL TEST WERE ADMINISTERED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE RETURNING TO THE BRANCH FACILITY WITH A LOAD OF DRUMS THE DRIVER HAD TO STOP QUICKLY ON THE HIGHWAY. AS HE EXITED THE HIGHWAY THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING OUT HIS VEHICLE. HE STOPPED AND DISCOVERED ONE 16 GALLON METAL DRUM HAD TIPPED OVER. HE UPRIGHTED THE DRUM AND ABSORBED THE SPILL WITH PIG MATS. HE PLACED THE USED PIG MATS BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER ESTIMATES 3 GALLONS OF THE PARTS WASHER SOLUTION WERE ABSORBED AND 4 GALLONS WERE RELEASED ONTO THE HIGHWAY. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE HAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 7979 PALM AVE HIGHLAND, CA FOR TREATMENT/ DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER REVIEWED PROPER LOAD LOCKING TECHNIQUES REQUIRED FOR MATERIAL TRANSPORTATION.

PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS LOADED ONTO VEHICLE AT 1200, APPROXIMATELY 1220, THE DRIVER NOTICED AN ODOR APPARENTLY COMING FROM THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER PULLED INTO AN EMPTY PACKAGING LOT TO INVESTIGATE. HE NOTICED A LIQUID COMING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. HE CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND MADE THE APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THAT PACKAGE ALONG WITH 3 OTHERS LIKE PACKAGES WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: WHILE EN ROUTE TO DELIVERY, BURLINGTON MOTOR CARRIERS DRIVER WAS FORCED TO STOP SUDDENLY FOR TRAFFIC IN DETROIT METRO AREA. WHEN HE BRAKED THE LOAD SHIFTED FORWARD IN THE TRAILER. ONE DRUM OF PAINT OVERTURNED. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL WAS CONTRACTED TO REMEDY THE SITUATION. ONCE AT THE SCENE,MPC LOCATED THE OVERTURNED DRUM AND IDENTIFIED 14 OTHER DRUMS THAT HAD SUSTAINED VARYING DEGREE OF DAMAGE. THE DRUMS HAD SHIFTED FORWARD AND HAD WEDGED TOGETHER. SOME OF THE DRUMS HAD BEEN DAMAGED NEAR THE TOPS CAUSING THE LIDS TO COME OFF. MPC SECURED THE LIDS ON ALL DRUMS THAT THEY COULD. THE REMAINDER OF THE DRUMS HAD THE CONTENTS PUMPED INTO NEW DRUMS. IN ALL 11 DRUMS WERE DAMAGED TO THE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

CHESI PERSONNEL INITIATED A CLEAN UP OPERATION;ALL SPILL MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AT OUR FULLY LICENSED TSDF. column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column168: DURING THE EARLY MORNING OF AUGUST 17, 1999 A LIMITED QUANTITY PACKAGE OF EXCEPTED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, BEING RETURNED TO THE MALLINCKRODT NUCLEAR PHARMACY FOR DISPOSAL FELL, UNNOTICED FROM THE BACK OF THE COURIER'S VAN. WHEN HE BECAME AWARE OF THE LOSS, THE DRIVER RETRACED HIS STEPS, BUT TO NO AVAIL.  THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN THE STREET BY A CIVILIAN AND TAKEN TO THE LOCAL US POST OFFICE.  POSTAL AUTHORITIES OPENED THE CASE, REALIZED ITS CONTENTS AND CALLED BOTH THE NYC POLICE AND THE MALLINCKRODT HICKSVILLE PHARMACY.  THE POST OFFICE WAS EVACUATED OF APPROX 30 EMPLOYEES FOR 4 HOURS UNTIL THE MALLINCKRODT RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER AND THE NEW YORK CITY BUREAU OF RADIOLOGIC HEALTH INSPECTOR INSPECTED THE CASE AND DECLARED THE SITUATION SAFE AND OF NO DANGER TO THE PUBLIC.  THE CASE WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE HICKSVILLE PHARMACY.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO MEET HIS RESPONSIBILITIES IN 2 AREAS: 1ST-HE FAILED TO SECURE THE CARGO WITH THE SPIDER NET SPECIFICALLY PROVIDED TO PREVENT THE MOVEMENT AND LOSS OF THE CASES AND HE FAILED TO SECURELY LOCK AND DOUBLE CHECK HIS CARGO DOOR UPON CLOSING THE VAN  2ND-HE FAILED TO FOLLOW THE ESTABLISHED PROCEDURE FOR NOTIFYING ALL THE CONCERNED PARTIES AFTER UNCOVERING HIS LOSS. THE EMERGENCY PROCEDURE PROVIDED TO THE DRIVER IN HIS MANUAL AND STRESSED IN TRAINING CLASSES, STIPULATES THE PARTIES TO BE NOTIFIED AT ONE; AND A CELLUAR TELEPHONE WAS SUPPLIED FOR JUST SUCH AN EMERGENCY.  THE DRIVER WAS SUPPLIED WITH AN EMERGENCY TELEPHONE LIST: 6 NUMBERS FOR THE PRESIDENT OF MEDICAL DELIVERY SERVICES, 2 NUMBERS FOR THE MANAGER OF MEDICAL DELIVERY SERVICES, 2 NUMBERS FOR THE MALLINCKRODT PHARMACY AND THE RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER, HOME NUMBERS OF THE PHARMACY MANAGER AND THE RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER, 3 NUMBERS FOR THE NY STATE DEPARTMENT OF LABOR AND THE NY CITY POLICE DEPT 911 EMERGENCY NUMBER.  INSTEAD OF CALLING THE ABOVE PARTIES, THE DRIVER RETRACED HIS ROUTE LOOKING FOR THE MISSING PIECE.  WHEN THE SEARCH BORE NO RESULTS, HE WENT ONTO MANHATTAN (2 HOURS LATER) TO BEGIN ANOTHER ROUTE.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN TERMINATED AFTER A REVIEW OF HIS ACTIONS AND HIS FAILURE TO FOLLOW ESTABLISED PROCEDURES.  THESE PROCEDURES WERE THROUGHLY EXPLAINED IN TRAINING CLASSES ATTENDED BY HIM AS RECENTLY AS SEPTEMBER 1998.

column168: (A - C) A BOX TRUCK DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO A CUSTOMER. HE WAS TRAVELING ON 287 N, CLOSE TO EXIT 10 IN EDISON, NJ.  TRAFFIC UNEXPECTANTLY STOPPED AND THE DELIVERY VEHICLE STRUCK THE BACK OF A TRACTOR TRAILER. DUE TO THE FORCE OF IMPACT, ONE 50 GLLON DRUM OF VORTEX (OXIDIZER AND CORROSIVE), ONE 5 GALLON PAIL OF TRISTAR L2000 XP (CORROSIVE), ONE 5 GALLON PAIL OF ET PHASE 1 SANITIZER (CORROSIVE) AND ONE 5 GALLON PAIL OF PANTASTIC (NO HAZ DETERGENT) LEAKED OUT OF THE BOX TRUCK. IN ADDITION, ANTIFREEZE WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE ENGINE AREA.  THE DELIVERY DRIVER PLACED HAZARD TRIANGLES ON THE ROADWAY TO HELP DIVERT TRAFFIC WITH THE HELP OF AN OFF-DUTY MIDDLESEX COUNTY SHERIFF, WHO ALSO REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO 911.  THE DELIVERY DRIVER AND THE MIDDLESEX COUNTY SHERIFF INHALED NOXIOUS FUMES ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILL AND WERE TRANSPORTED TO JFK HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION AND RELEASED.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER THAT WAS STRUCK MOVED FORWARD AND SECONDARILY STRUCK A VOLKSWAGEN. THE STATE POLICE REPORTED THAT NEITHER OF THE TWO OTHER DRIVER WERE INJURED AND CHOSE TO LEAVE THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT WITHOUT SEEKING ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION. THE SEMI TRAILER WAS REPORTED TO HAVE RECEIVED ONLY MINOR DAMAGE.  THE VOLKSWAGEN WAS ALSO REPORTED TO HAVE HAD ONLY MINOR DAMAGE. THE BOX TRUCK WAS  EXTENSIVELY DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF HEAVY IMPACT.  THE MOTOR WAS PUSHED INTO THE DRIVERS CAB, THE TRANSMISSION CRACKED IN HALF AND THE DRIVE SHAFT WAS HEAVILY BENT.  THE NJ STATE POLICE ESTIMATE THAT IMPACT WAS IN THE 30 MPH RANGE.  THE INCIDENT WAS RESPONDED TO BY THE MIDDLESEX COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM, THE NJ STATE POLICE, THE EDISON FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE NJ DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION, THE NJ DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND THE US ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY.  THE INTERSTATE HIGHWAY WAS TOTALLY CLOSED DOWN FROM APPROX 8AM - 1:30PM.  THE LEAKING CONTAINERS FROM THE BOX TRUCK WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUMS BY THE MIDDLESEX COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM. THE TRUCK AND THE NJDOT WERE PRESENT DURING THE DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURE, TO VERIFY THAT THE TRUCK WAS DECONTAMINATED IN AN APPROPRIATE MANNER.  THE TRUCK AND PRODUCT DECONTAMINATION WERE COMPLETED AT APPROX 8PM.  THE SALVAGE AND OVERPACKED PRODUCTS WERE THEN RETURNED TO THE FACILITY OF ORIGIN IN AVENEL, NJ FOR PROCESSING.  THE TRUCK WAS IMPOUNDED BY THE NJ STATE POLICE FOR INSPECTION.  THE INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE TRUCK WAS IN GOOD WORKING CONDITION. IN ORDER TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE, THE DRIVER WILL BE DISCIPLINED FOR UNSAFE DRIVING.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLERS NOTICED PROFUSE COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. column168: THE ASHLAND DRIVER WAS GOING TO A CUSTOMER FOR A DELIVERY. JUST BEFORE HE CROSSED THE DUMBARTEN BRIDGE HE PULLED OVER TO DO A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF HIS TRAILER. DURING THE INSPECTION, HE NOTICED A LEAK IMMEDIATELY DIKED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT BOOMS AND SODA ASH. NEXT, THE DRIVER WENT TO THE TOLL BRIDGE AND ASKED THEM TO NOTIFY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OF THE LEAK ON HIS TRUCK. THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED 1-800-ASHLAND OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED. ( 1-800-ASHLAND IS ASHLAND CHEMICAL'S EMERGENCY NOTIFICATION NUMBER) FINALLY, THE DRIVER TRIED TO STOP THE LEAK INSIDE THE TRAILER, BUT THE DRUM WAS NOT ACCESSIBLE. AT SOME POINT DURING THE INCIDENT, THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED. MATT ROBERTSON WROTE THE REPORT FOR THIS INCIDENT- NUMBERED 496627. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, BETTER INSPECTION OF WOODEN PALLETS WILL BE CONDUCTED.

RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE FOR PROCESSING. CONTAINED, SOLIDIFIED AND PROCESSED THE MATERIAL. PLACED IN BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES. I WORE THE PROPER P.P.E. DROPPED PKG CAUSED LEAKAGE. HUB MANAGER SHOULD PKG HANDLING.
NO DAMAGE, COULD NOT BE SHIPPED IN ORIGINAL CONTAINER BECAUSE DAMAGED BY ANOTHER LEAKER. BALANCE RE-PACKED IN A  YELLOW SALVAGE CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

BNSF TRAINMASTER NOTICED STEAM VAPOR CLOUD EMANATING FROM TANK CAR AFTER THIS CAR WAS SWITCHED INTO REPAIR TRACKS. BNSF & CONTRACT REDPONDERS FOUND CAR EJECTING PRODUCT (NALCO PR-4218, 48% AQUEOUS SOLUTION) VIA SAFETY VENT & 165 PSI RUPTURE DISC. EJECTED PRODUCT POLYMERIZED INTO POPCORN SIZE PIECES OR IN A SEMI- POLYMERIZED STATE. WATER WAS PUMPED INTO THE TANK'S INTERNAL HEATER COIL SYSTEM TO STABALIZE THE PRODUCT BY COOLING CAR DOWN. AT 0700 CDST, LOCAL AUTHORITIES INSTITUTED A 3000 FT. DOWNWIND EVACUATION ( WESTERLY DIRECTION), AFFECTING APPROX. 2200 STUDENTS & FACULTY OF A NEARBY HIGH SCHOOL: APPROX. 300 RESIDENTIAL & COMMERCIAL BUSINESS POPULACE: AND PORTIONS OF INTERSTATE 35 HIGHWAY. AT 0930 CDST, THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AFTER EVACUATION DISTANCE WAS REDUCED TO 750 FT. OR PORTIONS OF TEMPLE YARD ONLY. OFFICIALS AT THE LOCAL HIGH SCHOOLS OPTED TO CLOSE THE SCHOOL FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE DAY. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES ON HAND CONCLUDED THAT THE PRODUCT REACTION WAS CAUSED BY EITHER OR ALL OF THE FOLLOWING FACTORS: CONTAMINANT IN TANK CAR, SUCH AS IRON OXIDE: LOSS OF EFFECTIVE INHIBITOR: LACK OF OXYGEN: OR HEAT IN EXCESS OF 140 DEGREES F (AMBIENT OUTSIDE HIGH TEMPERATURE WAS OVER 100 DEGREES F FOR SEVERAL DAYS). EJECTED PRODUCT ON GROUND WAS SCRAPED & PILED ON PLASTIC FOR NALCO (SHIPPER) TO ARRANGE FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL. APPROX. 2 TO 3 CUBIC YARDS WAS GATHERED. PRODUCT THAT WAS EJECTED ONTO THE CAR & OTHER FREIGHT EQUIPMENT WAS WASHED DOWN AT TEMPLE DIESEL CLEANING FACILITY & THIS WASTEWATER WAS RETAINED IN STORAGE TANK FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL. AFTER PRODUCT IN TANK CAR STABILIZED, THE 165 PSI RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED & THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION THAT IS ANOTHER NALCO FACILITY.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: CAR REPORTED VENTING IN YARD & IT WAS ISOLATED. BNSF RESOPNDERS FOUND VAPOR RELEASE BYPASSING RUPTURE DISC IN SAFETY VENT. ALL MOUNTING BOLTS TIGHT WHEN CHECKED. CAUSE OF SEAL FAILURE IN SAFETY VENT NOT DETERMINTED. CERAMIC FRANGIBLE DISC WAS REPLACED & VENTING CEASED. CAR CHECKED PERIODICALLY UNTIL DEPARTURE WITH NO FURTHER RELEASE. SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED TO SEND CAR TO HOME SHOP FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION & APPLICABLE REPAIRS TO THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.

CAR STANDING ON REPAIR TRACKS FOR CENTER PLATE WORK NEEDED LOAD ADJUSTMENT. BNSF CONTRACTOR FOUND DISPOSABLE INFLATABLE DUNNAGE BAGS COLLAPSED RESULTING IN LOAD SHIFT OF BAGS WHICH OUT INTO BOTTOM LAYER OF ADJACENT PRODUCT BAGS. CONTRACTOR CLEANED SPILLED PRODUCT & ADJECTED 16 PALLETS OF PRODUCT IN DOORWAY AREA. CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER CENTER PLATE WORK COMPLETED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: CAR REPORTED VENTING IN YARD& IT WAS ISOLATED. BNSF RESOPNDERS FOUND FRANGIBLE DISC REMOVED & NOT REPLACED. ICE BAGS APPLIED AROUND SAFETY VENT TO RESIDUE VENTING VAPOR.SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE REPLACED FRANGILBLE FRANGILBLE DISC BY 1215 CDST ON 8/26. SHIPPER APPARENTLY REMOVED DISC DURING UNLOADING PROCESS & FAILED TO REPLACE IT PRIOR TO RELEASING RESIDUE CAR THEIR FACILITY.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE TRAILER #2998, OUR PROCESSING PLANT EMPLOYEE NOTICED A RELEASE OF LIQUID FROM AN UPRIGHT BOX. THE BOX WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN A PLASTIC DRUM. THE AREA, ON WHICH THE RELEASE OCCURRED, WAS DECONTAMINATED. TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THE SAME INCIDENTS, WE WILL REVIEW THE REQUITED CLOSURE METHODS WITH THE SHIPPER (GENERATOR/CUSTOMER).

THE CARTON WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT CAUSING THE SPILL. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN IN CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

THE PAIL WAS PUNCTURED BY SOME UNKNOWN OBJECT CAUSING THE SPILL. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL,STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN IN CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

column62: Over-pressurized; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE IS A TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT. THIS VEHICLE WAS ATTEMPTING A RIGHT TURN FROM ROUTE 59 ON TO JUNCTION 44 WHICH IS A TWO LANE ROAD. THE VEHICLE ROLLED ON ITS SIDE BLOCKING BOTH LANES OF TRAFFIC. PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE VENT VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANK APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON AND ANOTHER GALLON OR SO WAS LOST IN TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT.

NARRATIVE:  WHILE RETARPING A ROLLOFF CONTAINER, A SUPERIOR DRIVER DISCOVERED A SMALL PUDDLE OF MERCURY AT THE END OF A FLATBED TRUCK HOLDING CONTAINER FOR DIRECT SHIPMENT.  THE SOURCE WAS A MERCURY KEG FROM THE SUPERIOR RECYCLIGHTS FACILITY IN TALLAHASSEE, FLORIDA.  THE MERCURY WAS DESTINED FOR DFG MERCURY CORP., AND SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES WAS ACTING AS TRANSPORTER.  THE MORNING INSPECTIONS DID NOT INDICATE ANY VISIBLE SIGN, SO THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASE OCCURRED SOME TIME LATER IN THE MORNING.  A BERM WAS CREATED AND ALL VISIBLE MERCURY WAS VACUUMED UP WITH A HEPAVAC, AND TARPED OFF.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING WE RAN SEVERAL SWIPE TESTS TO DETERMINE IF THERE WAS ANY FURTHER CONTAMINATION,  ALONG WITH THREE SAMPLES OF ASPHALT WHERE THE MERCURY HAD BEEN FOUND.  ALL PARTS OF THE FLATBED TRAILER THAT HAD POTENTIAL FOR CONTAMINATION WERE DECONED WITH A NITRIC ACID SOLUTION.  ALL PORTIONS OF THE TRAILER THAT CONTAINED POROUS SURFACES WERE PLACED IN A CUBIC YARD BOX, ALONG WITH ALL PPE, TARPS, BERMS, AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL, CONSIDERED HAZARDOUS FOR MERCURY, AND SENT TO HAZARDOUS LANDFILL FOR TREATMENT.  THE DECON SOLUTION WAS ALSO CHARACTERIZED AS HAZARDOUS FOR MERCURY, AND WAS DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE AT A WASTEWATER TREATMENT FACILITY.

AFTER REVIEWING ACCIDENT REPORTS AND INTERVIEWING OUR PEOPLE WHO RESPONDED TO INCIDENT,   MY CONCLUSION IS THAT THERE WAS NO MATERIAL SPILLAGE, AND OTHER THAN PICKING UP TOOLS AND HOSES THAT HAD FALLEN OFF THE TRUCK, THERE WAS NO OTHER CLEAN-UP. CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT WAS DRIVER FATIGUE.  EVEN THOUGH THE DRIVER WAS WELL WITHIN HIS DRIVING HOURS.  HE HAD DRIVEN 6.75 HOURS AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, LEAVING HIM 1.25 HOUR TO LEGALLY DRIVE.  DRIVER HAD STOPPED FOR COFFEE 8 MILES PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT, AT A TRUCK STOP. DRIVER ALLOWED THE TANKER TO DRIFT OFF THE MAIN ROAD AND PROCEEDED TO GO UP THE MERIDIAN BETWEEN THE NORTH AND SOUTH BOUND LANES.  HE HIT A NUMBER OFF WASHOUTS, THAT CAUSED MODERATE DAMAGE TO THE UNDERCARRAGE OF THE TRACTOR AND TANKER.  AT NO TIME DID THE TANK OVER TURN OR FAIL. SAFETY MEETINGS AFTER THIS EVENT, DISCUSSED DRIVER FATIGUE, AND KNOWING WENT IT IS TIME TO SHUT DOWN AND REST.

column168: ON AUGUST 5, 1999, AT ABOUT 8:14 AM, DCC, INC. HAD A SPILL OF 250 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE(10%) AT 3800 LEXINGTON, HIGHLAND PARK, TEXAS.  THIS WAS AT A CITY POOL. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND MY DRIVER CALLED ME IMMEDIATELY. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT MADE A SMALL DAM FROM SOME CHEMICAL THEY HAD (SODIUM BICARB?) TO STOP ANY FURTHER CHLORINE FROM ENTERING THE STORM SEWER. WHEN I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE THEY HAD ALREADY LEFT, LEAVING A POLICE OFFICER TO MONITOR ANY TRAFFIC AND CLEAN UP. WE USED THIOSULFATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE CHLORINE.  WE USED SAND TO SOAK UP THE CHLORINE THEN SHOVELED IT INTO A CONTAINMENT TANK.  CONTAINMENT TANK WAS BROUGHT BACK TO DCC, WHERE WE WILL FURTHER NEUTRALIZE OR BALANCE PH THEN DISPOSE OF THE PH BALANCED AND NEUTRALIZED WATER THROUGH SEWER DRAIN AND SAND WILL BE USED ON OUR LOT. WE ALSO MIXED SEVERAL TEN GALLON BUCKETS(A TOTAL OF ABOUT 30 POUNDS) OF SODIUM THIOSULFATE WHICH WAS POURED INTO THE STORM DRAIN TO HELP NEUTRALIZE THE CHLORINE, WHICH ACCIDENTALLY MAY HAVE ENTERED INTO THE STORM DRAIN. WHEN I CONTACTED TNRCC THE NEXT MORNING, LAURIE WOOTEN ASKED ME TO CHECK THE SPILL THIS MORNING AND SEND YOU MY REPORT. UPON GOING BACK THE NEXT MORNING I TOOK CHLORINE AND P-H TESTS APPROXIMATELY  EVERY 500 FEET FOR ABOUT A MILE.  THESE RESULTS WERE FOR THE FIRST APPROXIMATELY 4 TENTHS OF A MILE.  PH 7.6 TO 8.0, CHLORINE LEVEL AT ZERO.  AT ABOUT 1/2 MILE DROPS TO 7.6 TO 7.4 AND ZERO CHLORINE.  AT FITZHUGH STREET APPROXIMATELY PH DROPS TO 7.3 AND ZERO CHLORINE. UNFORTUNATELY DURING MY WALK DOWN THE CREEK I DID NOTICE ABOUT 60 DEAD CATFISH APPROXIMATELY TWO TO FOUR INCHES LONG. LATER IN THE DAY THE TOWN OF HIGHLAND PARK INFORMED US THAT A CITY MAIN HAD BEEN BROKEN AND A MAN WHO RAISED FISH IN HIS FISH POND HAD OPENED A VALVE UPSTREAM AND RELEASED SOME DEAD FISH.  CITY HAS ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY AND HAS ALREADY CLEANED UP THE FISH.  THIS BEING SAID I COULD SEE NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT FROM THE SPILL.
WHILE TRANSPORTING TO CUSTOMER, TWO-WHEELER IN BACK OF TRAILER CAME LOOSE AS IT'S TIP SLICED THE PLASTIC TOTE.

column168: CARRIER WAS STEVENS TRANSPORT.  PRODUCT WAS STORED IN TRAILER AT STEVENS TRANSPORT TERMINAL IN DALLAS, TX WAITING TO BE SHIPPED.  FIRE WAS SPOTTED BY STEVENS TRANSPORT PERSONNEL AND DALLAS FIRE DEPT. NOTIFIED THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED BY FIRE DEPARTMENT THE CLEAN UP,  REMEDIATION AND DISPOSAL WAS COMPLETED BY BOOTS ON COOTS.  PPG TECHNICAL MANAGER WAS ON SITE FOR ASSISTANCE.  THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT IS UNKNOWN.  IT IS SPECULATED THAT PRODUCT MAY HAVE BEEN CONTAMINATED WITH BORATE AND ALUMINUM THAT CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SELF-HEAT AND IGNITE.  THE AUGUST TEMPERATURE IN DALLAS IS AROUND 100F.  THE MATERIAL WAS PACKAGED IN ONE POUND PLASTIC POUCHES WITH 50 POUCHES / FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE PLASTIC BAGS MELTED AND THE BOXES BURNED.  ALTHOUGH ACTUAL CAUSE WAS NEVER DETERMINED PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE MARKET AND WAS/IS NO LONGER PRODUCED.

column168: THIS REPORT IS FOR THE TRANSPORTATION-RELATED RELEASE OF BORON TRIFLUORIDE(BF3) GAS FROM A TUBE TRAILER ON AUGUST 2, 1999.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED ON ROUTE 12 IN BATON ROUGE, LA (INCIDENT #99-4263.) THE BF3 GAS RELEASED ON AUGUST 2, 1999 WAS MANUFACTURED BY ALLIEDSIGNAL IN MARCUS HOOK,   PA. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) FOR BF3 IS ATTACHED.  THE BF3 WAS BEING TRANSPORTED AS A COMPRESSED GAS FROM MARCUS HOOK, PA TO BEAUMONT, TX IN TUBE TRAILER TT-849 BY QUALITY CARRIERS (FORMERLY CHEMICAL LEAMAN).  TT-849 IS EQUIPPED WITH SIX (6) TUBES MANIFOLDED TOGETHER. DURING TRANSPORTATION ON AUGUST 2, THE CONTENTS OF EACH TUBE WERE PHYSICALLY ISOLATED BY CLOSED VALVES.  THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE WAS FROM TUBE 5 ON TT-849.  THE TUBE IS EQUIPPED WITH A BULL PLUG ASSEMBLY AT EACH END.  EACH BULL PLUG ASSEMBLY INCLUDES A SAFETY RELIEF CLUSTER TO  PREVENT A CATASTROPHIC RELEASE DUE TO EXCESSIVE TEMPERATURE AND OVERPRESSURIZATION. EACH BULL PLUG ASSEMBLY IS ATTACHED TO THE TUBE BY THREADING IT IN WITH STRAIGHT-TYPE THREADS.  AN O-RING PROVIDES A PRESSURE-SEAL BETWEEN THE TUBE AND THE BULL PLUG ASSEMBLY. AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM ON AUGUST 2, 1999, AS TT-849 WAS TRAVELING WEST ON ROUTE 12 IN BATON ROUGE, LA, THE QUALITY CARRIERS DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK OF BF3 GAS COMING FROM THE TUBE TRAILER AND REPORTEDLY STOPPED.  THE BATON ROUGE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, AND AS A SAFETY PRECAUTION, THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS SET UP WATER SPRAYS OVER TT-849 (THE BF3 WOULD  HAVE REACTED IMMEDIATELY WITH THE HUMIDITY IN THE AIR).  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE ALSO RESPONDED, CLOSING A SECTION OF ROUTE 12 AND EVACUATING THE AREA IN A 1/4 MILE RADIUS INCLUDING 11 HOMES. ALLIEDSIGNAL PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE FROM ITS FACILITIES IN BATON ROUGE AND GEISMAR, LA, AND MARCUS HOOK, PA.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE U.S. EPA AND LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY(DEQ) ALSO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  ALLIEDSIGNAL REPORTED THE RELEASE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AND WAS ASSIGNED REPORT #493587.  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE ASSIGNED INCIDENT #99-4263. THE BF3 GAS WAS LEAKING FROM THE TUBE 5 ON TT-849 FROM THE BULL PLUG ASSEMBLY AT THE MANIFOLDED END OF TUBE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 5:40 AM ON AUGUST 3, 1999, ALLIEDSIGNAL PERSONNEL STOPPED THE LEAK BY SEALING THE BULL PUG ASSEMBLY WITH DEVCON(LIQUID STEEL).  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 AM, THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF TUBE 5 (EXCEPT FOR SOME RESIDUAL BF3 GAS AT A PRESSURE OF 0 PSIG) WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TUBE TRAILER (TT-701). SHORTLY THEREAFTER, TUBE TRAILERS TT-849 AND TT-701 WERE TRANSPORTED TO ALLIEDSIGNAL'S FACILITY IN BATON ROUGE, LA, AND THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE ENDED THE EVACUATION OF THE AREA AND RE-OPENED ROUTE 12.  LATE IN THE EVENING ON AUGUST 3, TUBE TRAILERS TT-849 AND TT-701 WERE TRANSPORTED TO ALLIEDSIGNAL'S FACILITY IN GEISMAR, LA, AND AS OF THIS WRITING ARE STILL PRESENT AT THAT LOCATION. REPRESENTATIVES FROM U.S. EPA AND LOUISIANA DEQ MONITORED THE ATMOSPHERE AND THE WATER RUNOFF DURING THE INCIDENT.  THE MONITO

ALSO ATTACHED TO THE BOX WAS AN AIRWAY BILL.  SIDE 1, 2,3 AND 4 OF THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD NOTHING.  UPON INSPECTION OF INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND:1 METAL RECEPTACLE OF (RAIN & STAIN GUARD), UNDER PRESSURE @ 6.6 OUNCES, 2 METAL RECEPTACLES OF (HONCHOS BOOT SPRAY).  @ 10 OUNCES EACH, 1 OF 10 OUNCE RECEPTACLES LEAKED ALL ITS CONTENTS, DUE TO THE CLOSURE BEING BROKEN OFF. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0920 HOURS THE WOODSTOCK SWITCHER HAD PULLED THE DUPONT PLANT AND DISCOVERED TANK CAR GATX 31356, LOAD HYDROGEN PEROXIDE LEAKING. CURTIS HICK ASHLAND DRIVER WAS DELIVERING APPROXIMATELY 1,000 GALLONS OF N. BUTYL ACETATE TO OUR CUSTOMER AKZO NOBEL. AKZO IS LOCATED LESS THAN A MILE FROM THE BIRMINGHAM FACILITY. ASHLAND'S DRIVER PULLED INTO CUSTOMER LOCATION. RECEIVING PERSONNEL CHECKED THE RECEIVING TANK, SIGNED THE SHIPPING PAPERS ALL APPROPRIATE HOSE CONNECTIONS WERE SECURED WITH VELCRO STRAPS. THE DISCHARGE AND RECEIVING VALVES WERE OPEN AND THE PTO WAS ENGAGED. AFTER ABOUT FIFTEEN MINUTES CURTIS CLIMBED ON TOP THE BULK TRAILER AND NOTICED THE TANK WAS STILL FULL OF N. BUTYL ACETATE. CURTIS  THEN WALKED THE HOSE TOWARDS THE PUMP ENGAGED THE PUMP. A FEW MINUTES LATER BOTH CURTIS AND AKZO'S EMPLOYEE NOTICED PRODUCT COMING OFF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS SHUT AND THE PUMP WAS TURNED OFF IMMEDIATELY. WHILE CURTIS WAS CLOSING THE VALVES AND THE TRUCKS PUMP THE AKZO EMPLOYEE WAS USING BUCKETS TO CATCH THE LIQUID COMING DOWN THE DRAIN HOLES ON THE BACK OF THE TANKER. SEVERAL AKZO EMPLOYEE'S PADS AND OTHER EQUIPMENT. A TOTAL OF ONE HUNDRED AND SIXTY FOUR GALLONS WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKER. AKZO EMPLOYEE'S COLLECTED SIXTY FOUR GALLONS IN BUCKETS. FIFTY EIGHT GALLONS WAS CONTAINED ON TOP OF THE TANKER AND TWENTY TO TWENTY FIVE GALLONS WAS MOPPED UP ON THE CONTAINED PAD. APPROXIMATELY  20 GALLONS ESCAPED OFF CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SOIL THAT WAS CONTAMINATED. APPROXIMATELY TEN DRUMS  OF SOIL WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAMINATED AREA.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: 9:45PM, AUGUST 3, 1999 JACK STEWART WAS TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON I-90 THREE MILES WEST OF MITCHELL, SD. HE WAS DRIVING A TRACTOR THAT WAS PULLING A TRANSPORT FUEL TRAILER AND A PUP. HE WAS TRAVELING 70-72 MILES PER HOUR AND OBSERVED A VEHICLE PULLING THE TRAILER WITHOUT TAILLIGHTS OR VERY DIM LIGHTS. THIS VEHICLE WAS DRIVING SLOW AND AS JACK ENCOUNTERS THIS VEHICLE AT A HIGHER RATE OF SPEED, JACK HAS TO SWERVE INTO THE PASSING LANE TO MISS IT. WHILE DOING THIS HE THOUGHT HE CLIPPED THE CORNER OF THE TRAILER THAT HE ENCOUNTERED. THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE ON THE JACK'S TRUCK HAD THE HUB CAP & LUG NUT  COVERS MISSING.  AFTER SWERVING TO THE LEFT AND PULLING THE TRUCK BACK TO THE RIGHT TO CORRECT HIMSELF HE FELT THE TRUCK PULLING HARD. DURING THAT TIME OF CORRECTING HIMSELF THE PUP TRAILER TIPPED OVER AND HE LOOKED INTO THE MIRRORS ND COULD SEE THE SPARKS AND FLAMES.  HE PULLED OVER TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER AND RAN BACK AND PULLED THE TONGUE FROM THE MAIN TRAILER AND PULLED AWAY.  HE CALLED 911 ON HIS CELLULAR PHONE AND THE EMERGENCY CREWS RESPONDED.  THE DENR WAS CALLED FROM A OFFICER AT THE SCENE, AND THE DENR SAID TO LET THE PUP CONTINUE TO BURN UNTIL THE 3600 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS GONE.  MOST OF THE HAZMAT CLEANUP HAS BEEN PERFORMED, ALTHOUGH NO DOCUMENTATION HAS BEEN FORWARDED TO M G OIL COMPANY AS OF AUGUST 26, 1999.

THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON AUGUST 13, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 P.M. ON INTERSTATE 40, LOCATED AT MILE MARKER 66, MCDOWELL COUNTY, NORTH CAROLINA. JOHN SHOFNER A HARRY OWEN TRUCKING DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 40, AROUND BLACK MOUNTAIN, NC WHEN HE DID HIS TIRE CHECK. WHILE DOING HIS WALK AROUND JOHN OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS AND NOTICED A LEAKING DRUM. A 55 GALLON DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK AROUND THE TOP SEAL CAUSING THE CHEMICAL TO FLOW INTO THE TRAILER AND OUT ONTO THE GROUND. THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND THE DRUMS HAD NOT BEEN DISRUPTED DURING TRANSPORT. ONCE THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED THE DRIVER, JOHN SHFNER, CONTACTED HARRY OWEN TRUCKING. AFTER COLLECTING THE NECESSARY INFORMATION THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. THE NORTH CAROLINA HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE REGIONAL RESPONSE, OLD FORT FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND MCDOWELL COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT TEAM WERE ALL ON THE SCENE WITHIN 1 HOUR. FOR CLEAN UP TWO RECOVERY DRUMS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL. THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT WAS LOST WAS MINIMAL 5 TO 10 GALLONS. THE LEAK CAUSED BY THE SHIPPER NOT THE CARRIER. IT IS THE CARRIERS STANCE THAT IT COULD DO NOTHING DIFFERENT TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AND ITS THE SHIPPERS RESPONSIBILITIES TO TAKE STEPS TO PREVENT OVERLOADING OF DRUMS.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THIS PACKAGE SPILLED IN OUR SYSTEM. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DURING SPILL CLEANUP SIX 15 OZ. AEROSOL CANS OF DISINFECTANT WERE FOUND. THESE INNER CONTAINERS SAID "FLAMMABLE" ON THEM. THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS A COMPUTER BOX AND THERE WAS A LAPTOP CASE INSIDE. HOWEVER THE CONTENTS WERE THE AEROSOLS AS WELL AS A GOLD CHAIN. AS THE OUTER PACKAGING HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELING, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. F.A.A. AGENT JIM BURKE WAS NOTIFIED. FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURED THAT LED TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY. THE CONTAINER WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING. THIS RUPTURED THE CONTAINER AND ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE  CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. AN MSDS SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. THE FLASHPOINT FOR THE MATERIAL SHOWN ON THE MSDS WAS 105'F WHICH IS CLEARLY WITHIN THE RANGE FOR FLAMMABILITY. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE CONTAINER NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT JOE BALAS/FAA/EWR/CAFSO ON 08/31/1999 AT 12:30 (CST).

column168: CWX CHULA VISTA DRIVER ENTERED OUR PARKING LOT, AND STOPPED FOR DOCKING INSTRUCTIONS FOR HIS TRAILER. HE HAPPENED TO BE RIGHT ABOVE THE STORM DRAIN IN OUR LOT. APPROX. 1 GALLON SPILLED ONTO GROUND ABOUT 1 QUART ENTERED DRAIN. HE ENTERED YARD, DOCKED HIS TRAILER. TI WAS THAN DRIVER SPILLED LEAKING LIQUID. APPROX 2 MORE GALLONS LEAKED OUT BEFORE IT COULD BE CONTAINED. 4 15-GALLON PAILS WERE SET ATOP A PALLET, WITHOUT ANY BLOCKING OR BRACING DONE. IN TRANSIT,3 OF THE 4 PAILS FELL ONTO THEIR SIDES. A TRIPLE STACKED PALLET LOADED IN FRONT OF DRUMS FELL IN TRANSIT ON TOP PF THE PAILS, CRUSHING IN ITS SIDE. THE PRESSURE FROM THE PALLET FORCED LIQUID OUT FROM THE TOP OF THE PAIL. THE PAIL WAS ONLY ABOUT 3 GALLONS EMPTY FROM THE TOP OF PAIL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SPILLAGE STARTED WHEN THE DRIVER ENTERED CWX YARD. SAFETY SUPERVISOR (BILL FYFE) 911-FIRE DEPT, CHEMTREE AND FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL WERE ALL CALLED TO HELP CONTAIN AND CLEAN THE SPILL. MESSAGE WAS RELAYED TO LOADING SERVICE CENTER TO INSTRUCT WITH THEIR DOCKMEN THE IMPROPER LOADING OF THIS FREIGHT.

A PASSENGER CHECKED A BAG CONTAINING UNDECLARED FIREWORKS (POPS) FOR FLIGHT BETWEEN SAN AND SNA.  IN OAK, DURING THE OFFLOAD FOR TRANSFER TO ANOTHER AIRCRAFT, THE BAG BEGAN TO SMOLDER AND FILL THE BIN WITH SMOKE WHEN THE RAMP AGENT MOVED IT TO THE BELT LOADER.  THE RAMP AGENT SUSTAINED FIRST AID TYPE INJURY (NON-HOSPITALIZED) AND THE BAG WAS MOVED FROM THE VICINITY OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THE BAG WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN SNAP-POP FIREWORKS THT HAD BEGUN TO SMOLDER DUE TO THEIR FRICTION SENSITIVE NATURE.  THE SNAP POPS HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THEIR ORIGINAL PACKAGING AND PLACED IN THE PASSENGER'S BAGGAGE.  OAK EMERGENCY TEAMS RESPONDED AND THE STATION NOTIFIED FAA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

THE DRUM WAS PUT IN A PLASTIC-LINED RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED IN THE HAZMAT OS/D AREA.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE COLTON COMMAND CENTER, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE RECEIVING YARD.  DEVELOPED THE TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT, SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE, FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR, BY THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT WHILE THEY WERE INSPECTING THE INBOUND TRAIN IN RECEIVING YARD TRACK #207.  MANAGER COOPER REQUESTED THE COMMAND CENTER TO NOTIFY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND FOLLOW UP WITH NOTIFICATION TO RMCC. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON RECEIVING YARD AND MET WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND REPRESENTATIVES OF SAN BENARDINO COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE MTO TO MOVE THE CARS ON #208 TRACK, WHICH ALLOWED ACCESS TO THE LEAKING TANK ON THE #207 TRACK. INITIAL GROUND INSPECTION NOT PRODUCT TRAILS DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR, DRIPPING AT AN APPROXIMATE RATE OF ONE GALLON EVERY FIVE MINUTES.  THE PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE COVER THAT HOUSES THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE AND THE AIR LINE.  AFTER DISCUSSING THE POTENTIAL SOURCES OF THE RELEASE, THE ENTRY TEAM MADE IT'S WAY TO THE TOP OF THE CAR AND OPENED THE PROTECTIVE COVER. INSPECTION DEVELOP THE PRODUCT WAS BYPASSING THE THREADS OF THE LIQUID LINE WHERE THE BALL VALVE IS ATTACHED.  AFTER RECEIVING THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE VESSEL, WHICH STOPPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK, THE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE WAS REMOVED.  THE PIPE THREADS APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION,  AND IT WAS NOTED  THAT THAT THERE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ANY TYPE OF SEALANT ON THREADS.  TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE PIPE THREADS, AND THE BALL VALVE RE INSTALLED. IT APPEARS THAT AS THE PRESSURE WAS BUILDING IN THE CAR, THE LIQUID WAS BEING FORCED  UP THE LIQUID LINE AND BYPASSING THE PIPE THREADS AT THE BALL VALVE CONNECTION.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY GARY GERLACH, MTO, ANAHEIM, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE LOS NIETOS YARD.  MTO GERLACH HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY AN FRA INSPECTOR WHO WAS CONDUCTING MECHANICAL INSPECTIONS IN THE YARD, WHEN THEY NOTICED THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD DRIED PRODUCT TRAILS ON THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOS NIETOS YARD AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CAR ON YARD TRACK #006.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND DESIGN, LOCATED OUTSIDE OF THE WORK PLATFORM, WAS DISASSEMBLED, THE BUST DISC REMOVED, AND REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 165 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  IT APPEARS THE CAR WAS ROUGH HANDLED BURNING TRANSPORTATION, WHICH CAUSED A LIQUID SURGE, BURSTING THE FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FROM MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING LEAKING IM TANK.  MANAGER COOPER, DROVE TO THE ICTF, AND LOCATED THE ABOVE IM TANK STILL ON THE RAIL CAR IN TRACK #808.  THE LOWER PORTION OF THE IM TANK WAS COVERED WITH PRODUCT, AS WELL AS THE DECK OF THE RAIL CAR (VTTX 906310), AND THE FRONT OF THE TRAILING CONTAINER, CBHU 64761.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD COVERED THE EQUIPMENT.  THE IM TANK WAS REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR, DIAPER AND SET TO A CHASSIS, WHERE IT WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK CONTAINMENT AREA.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM SEVERAL AREAS ON THE BELLY OF THE IM TANK, WHERE THE EXTERNAL JACKET SEAMS WERE NOT SEALED.  AS THE TOP AND REAR VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE SECURE, IT WAS CONCLUDED THE TANK HAD FAILED.  THE EXACT LOCATION COULD NOT BE ASSESSED DUE TO THE TANK JACKET AND INSULATION.  THE RAIL CAR WAS SET OUT PENDING CLEANING, AND THE TRAILING CONTAINER WAS ALSO MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK AREA WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER, CMS, WHO STATED THEY WERE THE AGENT FOR UNION PACIFIC BULKTAINER SERVICES. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH BULKTAINER SERVICES, AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LEAKING IM TANK.  BULKTAINER SERVICES ARRANGED TO HAVE ANOTHER IM TANK(UPUU 530016) DELIVERED, AND TEC TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT TO THE REPLACEMENT TANK.  IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT, THE EXTERNAL JACKET AND INSULATION WAS REMOVED FROM THE LEAKING IM TANK.  EXTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE IM TANK WAS INCONCLUSIVE IN LOCATING THE EXACT SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  IT IS SUSPECTED THE TANK MAY HAVE FAILED AT ONE OF THE FORWARD BOLSTER WELDS.  ONCE THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS PACKAGED, CLEANING OF THE RAIL CAR AND THE FOLLOWING CONTAINER COMMENCED.  ONCE THEY WERE DEEMED CLEAN OF THE RESIDUE, THEY WERE RELEASED FOR  MOVEMENT.  THE DAMAGED TANK WAS RESTENCILED AND PLACARD FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO CMS, WHERE IT WILL BE INSPECTED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER, FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY,  WAS CONTACTED BY ITS PERSONNEL, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. DEVELOPED  AN OUTSIDE DRAYMAN WAS IN THE YARD ATTEMPTING TO PICK THE CONTAINER UP FOR DELIVERY, WHEN HE OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING NEAR THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO LOT#6 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON OPEN HEAD METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGH OUT THE CONTAINER.  THE DRUMS WERE INDIVIDUALLY RISER, RATHER THAN AN ENTIRE ROW BEING RISER. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE 6C, FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE LADING IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM.  PART WAY INTO THE CONTAINER, LOCATED ONE DRUM THAT WAS ON THE UPPER TIER THAT HAD RELEASED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS.  AS THE DRUMS HAD BEEN INDIVIDUALLY RISER, THE MG BOLT FROM AN ADJACENT FLOOR LOADED DRUM HAD ABRADED THE BOTTOM SIDE WALL OF THE TOP LOADED DRUM.  ALL OF THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED FOR DAMAGE.  A TOTAL OF 13 DRUMS WERE NOTED WITH DAMAGE FROM ABRASION AND WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  ALL THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVER PACK DRUMS AND SECURED.  AS THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS TO BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER, PER THEIR REQUEST, THE LADING WAS PLACED INTO A 40 FOOT CONTAINER, MOLU703685, AND SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS CLEANED AND RELEASED BACK TO THE VESSEL OPERATOR.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED TO HAVE BILLING PUT IN PLACE TO MOVE THE SECONDARY CONTAINER BACK TO THE POINT OF ORIGIN.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC, REPORTING LEAKING TANK CAR AT YERMO, CALIFORNIA. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FROM MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT YERMO, CALIFORNIA.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ALLEN WICKS, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO OPERATIONS, YERMO, WHO STATED THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FORCES HAD BEEN INSPECTING A TRAIN, LJ55X-16, IN YARD TRACK #206, WHEN THEY OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF THE ABOVE CAR.  THE DRIP WAS ESTIMATED TO BE 10 TO 15 DROPS PER MINUTE.  THE CARMEN MOVED AWAY FROM THE CAR AND DEPARTED THE AREA.  AS THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED NEAR THE CENTER OF THE TRAIN CONSIST, IT WAS LEFT IN PLACE PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED DAVE JOHNSON, PLANT MANAGER, PIONEER CHLOR ALKALI, HENDERSON, NEVADA, AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE WITH REPAIRING THE CAR. THE PIONEER TEAM ARRIVED YERMO, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THIS CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATING HANDLE THAT CONTROLS THE INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT FOR THE TOP OPERATING ROD WAS TIGHT AND THE OPERATING ROD ALSO APPEARED TO BE TIGHT.  A PIPE WRENCH WAS USED TO FURTHER TIGHTEN THE OPERATING ROD, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET IS SUPPLIED WITH A 4 INCH TO 2 INCH REDUCER, THAT ALSO CONTAINS A SECONDARY VALVE.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM THE 4 INCH BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WHERE IT IS THREADED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS ALSO TIGHTENED.  ONCE THE PRODUCT WAS DRAINED FROM BETWEEN THE INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE SECONDARY 2 INCH VALVE, IT WAS DETERMINED THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS CLEANED OF THE PRODUCT RESIDUE, AND THE GROUND AREA UNDER THE RAIL CAR WAS ALSO ADDRESSED.  THE GROSSLY CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO DRUMS. THE REMAINING GROUND AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED.  THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO PIONEER FOR TREATMENT.  THIS CAR WAS PREVIOUSLY REPAIRED ON AUGUST 7, 1999, AND HAS BEEN MOVING INTERNALLY WITHIN THE YARD.  IT APPEARS THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSENED DUE TO THE ADDITIONAL MOVEMENT BETWEEN INCIDENTS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES,  AND TO THE SHIPPER, FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: ON 08-17-99 AT APPROXIMATELY 0715 HOURS CTS MGR., M KELLY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC WITH REFERENCE TO THE ABOVE TANK CAR EMITTING A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD AND STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR THE CAR.  KELLY RESPONDED TO THE MUSKOGEE YARD AND UPON ARRIVAL INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE VAPOR WAS COMING FROM THE PACKING NUT OF THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  KELLY ADDED PACKING UNDER THE NUT AND TIGHTENED IT UNTIL THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEM-TREC WERE NOTIFIED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ROB MATTESON, ELF ATOCHEM, PORTLAND, OREGON, WHO STATED THEIR CUSTOMER,  JONES CHEMICAL HAD RECEIVED A TANK CAR THAT APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED TONY MARTINEZ, FOREMAN, JONES CHEMICAL, TORRANCE, AND DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CAR HAD BEEN SPOTTED TO THEIR FACILITY THE PREVIOUS EVENING, AND THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR AROUND THE MANWAY WAS COVERED WITH DRIED PRODUCT. THEY WERE CONCERNED WITH THE DRIED RESIDUE ON THE CAR AND WERE NOT ABLE TO EFFECT REPAIRS.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE JONES CHEMICAL FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC, LOCATED IN THE SAFETY VENT MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD GATX TRI-VENT, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AT THE  BURST DISC REMOVED AND REPLACE WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 165 POUND STAINLESS/ TEFLON DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, ALL OF WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE.  IT APPEARS THIS CAR WAS ROUGH HANDLED DURING TRANSPORT, CAUSING A LIQUID SURGE UP THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT, WHICH BURST THE FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE PLANT FOR UNLOADING.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C COOPER,MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS YERMO, CALIFORNIA REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR. SUPERVISOR VALDEZ STATED THE WEST END SWITCH JOB OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.AS THE CAR WAS A PLACARDED COMMIDTY IT WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT TOM DIPLEY WHO INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANIGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT A STANDARD GATX TRI-VENT MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, WAS DISASSEMBLED THE BURST DISC REMOVED AND REPLACE WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 165 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLE AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASE FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. IT APPEARS THIS CAR WAS SUBJECT TO AN OVER SPEED IMPACT CAUSING A LIQUID SURGE UP THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT, WHICH BURST THE FRANGIBLE DISC. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: LEE HAMMOND, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC THAT TANK CAR MWSX 29651 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHEN MOVED. SWITCH CREW ISOLATED THE CAR ON TRACK 13 AT MARSHALLTOWN, IA.SHIPPER CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC AND REPAIR OPTIONS DISCUSSED. SHIPPER WITH RESCAR TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS. PRIOR TO RESCARS RESPONSE. UNION PACIFIC FORCES APPLIED A NEW MANWAY GASKET AND TIGHTENED COVER BOLTS. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

H.L. BART REGIONAL MANAGER CTS WAS NOTIFIED BY RMC OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE VELASCO YARD IN FREEPORT TEXAS. TANK CAR GATX 66418 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. COVER PLATE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND CAR WAS SECURED. CAR WAS THEN FORWARDED TO BILLED DESTINATION.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Over-pressurized; Water Damage
column168: ON 081799  AT APPROX 0715HRS CTS MGR M KELLY WAS CONTACTED BY RMC WITH REFERENCE TO TANK CAR ONTX 105 LEAKING IN THE MUSKOGEE OK YARD. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE YARD M KELLY REPAIRED THE TANK CAR AND THEN INSPECTED TANK CAR ONTX 103 THAT HAD COME FROM THE SAME SHIPPER AND PLANT. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR KELLY FOUND IT LEAKING G FROM THE PACKING AROUND THE VALVE STEM ON THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE B END OF THE CAR.KELLY TRIED SEVERAL REPAIR METHODS TO STOP THE LEAK BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. KELLY THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WIL-GRO INDS AND ADVISED THEM THAT THE CAR WOULD NEED TO TRANSFERRED BEFORE IT COULD CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION. ON 081999 M KELLY AND M JOHNSON TRANSFERED THE CONTENTS OF THE ABOVE CAR INTO HRRX 122.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: THIS IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELS OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. 09/25/99 AT 2:19 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN D BUILDING OF OUR FACILITY LOCATED AT ARX AIR INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON OH 46177. PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS CARL BOHL AND JEFFREY KIDDER DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND RESPONDED TO SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIREBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY TESTED THE LEAKING LIQUID, PH READING 7. THEY THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND A 16 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF ISOPROPYL RUBBING ALCOHOL THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURE ON THE BOTTLE CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF THE ENTIRE 16 OUNCE OF THE ISOPROPYL RUBBING ALCOHOL. THE REMAINDER OF THE ITEMS IN THIS BOX WERE PRINTED MATERIALS, CLOTHING, AND A BROWN PLASTIC BOTTLE OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE NONE OF WHICH WERE REGULATED MATERIALS. THEY RESEALED THE ALCOHOL PLACED ALL THE CONTENTS BACK INSIDE THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX. PLACED THE BOX INSIDE TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND PLACED THE BAGGED MATERIALS INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS PLACED  INSIDE A HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING UPON FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE THREE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE ODOR FROM THIS SHIPMENT. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND RETURNED TO THERE WORK AREA. NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES REQUIRED MEDICAL ATTENTION. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELS CERTIFICATIONS FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.
DRIVER SCOTT CATES WAS MOVING PALLET CONTAINING THE SHIPMENT ACROSS DOCK WITH FORKLIFT. THE PALLET BROKE FROM UNDERSIDE RESULTING IN A PUNCTURE OF CTN CONTAINING POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE.

JACK GIACONA ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER WAS NOTIFIED AT 1550HRS OF A LEAKING TANKCAR AT SETTEGAST YARD. MGR GIACONA RESPONDED AND UTILIZED THE SERVICE OF EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND SECURE CAR. TANKCAR ASTX 2015 WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A FILL HOLE COVER GASKET OUT OF PLACE. GASKET WAS REPOSITIONED, FILL HOLE COVER RESECURED AND CAR FORWARDED TO BILLED DESTINATION. EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES USED BICARBONATE OF SODA TO NEUTRALIZE SPILLED PRODUCT ON TANK CAR SHELL.

THE HOSTLER MR GERLICH COULD SMELL A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TRLR 15-4316 A CLOSED LAREDO AS HE PULLED IT AWAY FROM THE DOCK. I HAD THE TRAILER PUT UP TO THE OUTBOUND DOCK. WHEN I OPENED THE DOOR A LIQUID WAS ON THE FLOOR AT THE BACK DOOR, AND THEN IT STARTED TO LEAK OUT THE FRONT. I PUT A SALVAGE UNDER THE FRONT TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. I CONTACTED THE SPILL CENTER AND HAD GARDNER COME OUT TO STRIP TRAILER AND SECURE THE LEAKING DRUM.
RESPONDED TO SPILL AT 7:35 USED PH TAPE ON SPILL WITH DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR STRONGER ALKALINE.  USING SODIUM BICARBONATE TO MIX WITH THE ALKALINE SPILL THEN PROCESS THROUGH DMP.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: EMG FIELD MANAGER, ALAN JENSEN WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE OGDEN YARD.  THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN SET OUT AND ISOLATED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND CONNECTED MGR JENSEN WITH THE SHIPPER,  ABF FREIGHT SERVICES.  ABF CONTRACTED WITH TW COMPANY TO HANDLE CLEANUP.  TW COMPANY UNLOADED THE TRAILER AND FOUND THAT A PALLET OF FIVE GALLON PAILS HAD NOT BEEN BLOCKED OR BRACED AND DID NOT HAVE SEPARATORS BETWEEN THE PAILS. ADDITIONALLY, OTHER MATERIAL HAD BEEN STACKED ON TOP OF THE PAILS.  A PAILS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE LOAD HAD BEEN CRUSHED FROM  THE WEIGHT MATERIAL STACKED ON TOP OF IT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED AND RELOADED AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT ON 8/26/99.

column42: AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED OR AMMONIA SOLUTIONS RELATIVE DENSITY LESS THAN .880 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: ON THE MORNING OF AUGUST 19,1999, JEFF MAULER, BRANCH MANAGER OF THE PAWNEE ROCK BRANCH, OF THE GREAT BEND COOP, AND FRED ROSS AN EMPLOYEE; CHANGED A FAULTY GAUGE ON A NURSE TANK. THE TANK WAS THEN FILLED TO APPROXIMATELY 80% FULL OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA (NH3). THE TANK WAS THEN PULLED IN LINE FOR CUSTOMER PICKUP. AROUND 1130 PM THAT NIGHT IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TANK WAS RELEASING NH3 AROUND THE GAUGE. THE PAWNEE ROCK VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED FIRST. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED RANDY STAGGS, THE ASST. BRANCH MANAGER OF PAWNEE ROCK. RANDY CONTACTED JEFF MAULER, BRANCH MANAGER AT PAWNEE ROCK. JEFF CONTACTED DENNIS NEELAND OPERATIONS MANAGER OF THE GREAT BEND COOP. THE PAWNEE ROCK FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED THE PAWNEE ROCK TOWN MARSHALL, BARTON COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT AS WELL AS THE GREAT BEND FIRE DEPARTMENT EMT UNIT. THE PAWNEE ROCK FIRE DEPARTMENT SET UP A PERIMETER APPROXIMATELY .1 OF A MILE FROM PLANT. THE RESPONDERS SENT THREE PERSONNEL INTO THE PLANT IN FULL BUNKERS AND SCBA, TO TRY TO TIGHTEN THE SCREWS AROUND GAUGE. ONE RESPONDER WAS OVERCOME BY THE NH3 AND CAME OUT ON HIS OWN POWER. THIS RESPONDER WAS TAKEN TO CENTRAL KANASA MEDICAL CENTER FOR EVALUATION AND RELEASED. JEFF MAULER THEN WENT IN WITH THE OTHER RESPONDERS AND TRIED TO PUMP OFF THE NURSE TANK. THE PROCEDURE DID NOT WORK, THE REASON IS NOT CLEAR AS THE PROCEDURE HAS WORKED SINCE THEN. THE DECISION TO BLEED OFF TANK IN WATER AT THE PLANT WAS DISMISSED AS THE WIND BLOWING FROM THE EAST, DRIFTING INTO THE TOWN OF PAWNEE ROCK. THE DECISION TO PULL THE TANK TO AN ISOLATED AREA WAS MADE. THE KANSAS HWY. PATROL, BARTON CO. SHERIFF, AND PAWNEE ROCK MARSHALL STOPPED TRAFFIC AS THE TANK WAS PULLED OUT THE PLANT. THE TANK WAS PULLED TO AN ISOLATED AREA, .2 MILE WEST, .5 MILE SOUTH, .5 MILE EAST, 1.5 MILE SOUTH, .7 MILE EAST, NORTH APPROXIMATELY 300 YARDS INTO A FIELD, FROM THE PLANT. AT THAT TIME THERE WAS NO WIND, THE VAPOR CLOUD WAS GOING STRAIGHT UP. THE FOLLOWING MORNING AT 7:00 AM, OF AUGUST 20, 1999, DENNIS NEELAND OBSERVED THE TANK STILL RELEASING PRODUCT, STILL NO PREVALENT WIND THE VAPOR CLOUD GOING STRAIGHT UP. AT ABOUT 9:50 AM THAT MORNING THE RELEASE HAD STOPPED AS THE TANK HAD DE-PRESSURIZED AND THE TANK WAS PULLED BACK TO THE PLANT, IN PAWNEE ROCK. THE GAUGE WAS THEN REPLACED. INVESTIGATION FOUND NO FOREIGN MATERIAL TO BE UNDER OR AROUND THE SEAL, CAUSE OF THE FAULTY SEAL NOT DETERMINED. THE TANK HAS BEEN IN SERVICE SINCE WITH NO PROBLEMS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED BY STATION ATTENDANT AS TO WHICH TANKS TO DROP INTO. DRIVER THOUGHT HE WAS DROPPING INTO A 10,000 GALLON NL TANK, WHEN IN FACT IT WAS A 4,000 GALLON DIESEL TANK.  WHEN THE TANK FILLED, THE BACK PRESSURE BLEW A HOLE IN THE DROP HOSE CAUSING A SPILL OF GASOLINE THAT RAN DOWN THE GAS STATION DRIVE AND INTO THE STORM SEWER.  MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL AND THE D.H.F.D. SOAKED UP FREE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WITH OIL ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE D.H.F.D. THEN FLUSHED OUT THE STORM SEWER TO THE OUTLET AT THE ROUGE RIVER WHERE MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL HAD SET UP OIL ABSORBENT PADS AND BOOMS.  THE DEARBORN HEIGHTS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AS WAS MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL.  ALSO CONTACTED WAS THE N.R.C. ON SITE BESIDES THE D.H.F.D. WERE THE WAYNE COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, MICHIGAN DEQ, SURFACE WATER QUALITY DIVISION (MR. EARL FRIESE, JR.) , AND THE U.S. COAST GUARD (MR. MARK A. MYERS).  EMERGENCY RESPONSE MANAGEMENT WAS BROUGHT IN TO DO A SITE INVESTIGATION AND DO SAMPLING AT THE SITE.  ON MAY 5, 2000, MR. PAUL J. OWENS OF THE MICHIGAN DEQ, EMERGENCY RESPONSE DIVISION CONCLUDED NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED WITH REGARD TO THIS INCIDENT.
